According to legend, this dance originated when {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|12=draft}} returned victorious from her conquest of {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|12=draft}}, and it was performed by the ancestors of the Abe clan during the Daijōsai. Another tradition at {{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha|ja|住吉大社|12=draft}} states that this dance originated when residents of the {{ill|Shichidō|ja|七道|12=draft}} beach in present-day {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市|12=draft}} welcomed the returning Empress Jingū by dancing with umbrellas. This tradition is believed to have evolved into the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Odori|ja|住吉踊り|12=draft}}.
The term {{ill|Kishi|ja|吉師|12=draft}} refers to clans involved in diplomacy and naval activities during the Yamato court era. Many of these clans were of foreign origin and were associated with the Abe clan.
== Classical Military Music "Kishimai" == '''Kishimai''' is also the title of a {{ill|wind band|ja|吹奏楽|12=draft}} composition by {{ill|Akira Ifukube|ja|伊福部昭|12=draft}}, best known for his work on {{ill|Godzilla|ja|ゴジラ|12=draft}}. Composed in {{ill|Shōwa 18 (1943)|ja|昭和18th year|12=draft}} at the request of the {{ill|Imperial Japanese Navy|ja|大日本帝国海軍|12=draft}}, the piece was completed in February of that year and premiered on April 8 under the baton of {{ill|Itsurō Hattori|ja|服部逸郎|12=draft}}, performed by the Tokyo Broadcast Wind Orchestra on NHK Radio.
According to Ifukube, the piece was reportedly played during the radio broadcast announcing the arrival of {{ill|Douglas MacArthur|ja|ダグラス・マッカーサー|12=draft}} at the {{ill|Atsugi Naval Airfield|ja|厚木海軍飛行場|12=draft}} on August 30, 1945, although it is unclear if it was performed live at the site.
Inspired by the name and legend of the now-forgotten "Kishimai," Ifukube composed the piece with his own interpretation. Structured in a {{ill|rondo form|ja|ロンド形式|12=draft}}, its second theme, a march, was later adapted for various films, including the {{ill|Self-Defense Forces|ja|自衛隊|12=draft}}' mobilization scenes in {{ill|Godzilla (1954 film)|ja|ゴジラ|12=draft}}. This adaptation became the "Fregate March," used in themes such as the frigate fleet of the {{ill|Japan Coast Guard|ja|海上保安庁|12=draft}} in ''Godzilla'' and the "Space War March," the main theme for ''{{ill|Battle in Outer Space|ja|宇宙大戦争|12=draft}}''. Among these, the arrangement for ''{{ill|Invasion of Astro-Monster|ja|怪獣大戦争|12=draft}}'' became widely known as the "Monster Zero March." This rendition was revisited in ''{{ill|Godzilla vs. Biollante|ja|ゴジラvsビオランテ|12=draft}}.''
Though forgotten after the war, "Kishimai" was "rediscovered" in the 1990s and was revived in May 2001. It is now occasionally performed by groups such as the {{ill|JGSDF Central Band|ja|陸上自衛隊中央音楽隊|12=draft}}.
