According to legend, this dance originated when [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]] returned victorious from her conquest of [[:en:Silla|Silla]], and it was performed by the ancestors of the Abe clan during the Daijōsai. Another tradition at [[:en:Sumiyoshi-taisha|Sumiyoshi Taisha]] states that this dance originated when residents of the {{ill|Shichidō|ja|七道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shichidō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 五畿七道|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 五畿七道|1=Gokishichidō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1196984}} beach in present-day [[:en:Sakai|Sakai]] welcomed the returning Empress Jingū by dancing with umbrellas. This tradition is believed to have evolved into the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Odori|ja|住吉踊り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Odori|qq=|1=Sumiyoshi Odori|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q20045159}}.
The term {{ill|Kishi|ja|吉師|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 吉士|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 吉士|1=kishi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q55526932}} refers to clans involved in diplomacy and naval activities during the Yamato court era. Many of these clans were of foreign origin and were associated with the Abe clan.
== Classical Military Music "Kishimai" == '''Kishimai''' is also the title of a {{ill|wind band|ja|吹奏楽|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wind band|qq=|1=wind music|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q28856774}} composition by [[:en:Akira Ifukube|Akira Ifukube]], best known for his work on [[:en:Godzilla (franchise)|Godzilla]]. Composed in [[:en:1943|Showa 18]] at the request of the [[:en:Imperial Japanese Navy|Imperial Japanese Navy]], the piece was completed in February of that year and premiered on April 8 under the baton of {{ill|Itsurō Hattori|ja|服部逸郎|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itsurō Hattori|qq=|1=Itsurō Hattori|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11516997}}, performed by the Tokyo Broadcast Wind Orchestra on NHK Radio.
According to Ifukube, the piece was reportedly played during the radio broadcast announcing the arrival of [[:en:Douglas MacArthur|Douglas MacArthur]] at the [[:en:Naval Air Facility Atsugi|Atsugi Naval Airfield]] on August 30, 1945, although it is unclear if it was performed live at the site.
Inspired by the name and legend of the now-forgotten "Kishimai," Ifukube composed the piece with his own interpretation. Structured in a [[:en:Rondo|rondo form]], its second theme, a march, was later adapted for various films, including the [[:en:Japan Self-Defense Forces|Self-Defense Forces]]' mobilization scenes in [[:en:Godzilla (franchise)|Godzilla (1954 film)]]. This adaptation became the "Fregate March," used in themes such as the frigate fleet of the [[:en:Japan Coast Guard|Japan Coast Guard]] in ''Godzilla'' and the "Space War March," the main theme for ''[[:en:Battle in Outer Space|Battle in Outer Space]]''. Among these, the arrangement for ''[[:en:Invasion of Astro-Monster|Invasion of Astro-Monster]]'' became widely known as the "Monster Zero March." This rendition was revisited in ''[[:en:Godzilla vs. Biollante|Godzilla vs. Biollante]].''
Though forgotten after the war, "Kishimai" was "rediscovered" in the 1990s and was revived in May 2001. It is now occasionally performed by groups such as the {{ill|JGSDF Central Band|ja|陸上自衛隊中央音楽隊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JGSDF Central Band|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 音楽隊 (陸上自衛隊)|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 音楽隊 (陸上自衛隊)|1=Japan Ground Self-Defense Force Band|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11664287}}.
